<B>Another email scam.  And this one looks authentic</B><BR>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2"><BR>Hail, Everquest customer, your email was randomly selected from our database of player emails. We have been asking these select few players whether or not they would like to participate in the upcoming SOL expansion beta test.<P>If you agree to sign up for the SOL beta test you will get to try out exclusive Shadows of Luclin armor, weapons and spells. Also, you will have access to the new SOL zones. If this wasn't enough, to urge our player base into helping us out, we will give the first 50 players to sign up an in game title "the tester" and a superb piece of equipment based on your character class and race.<P>In order to be accepted into the Shadows of Luclin Beta Test, You will need to email us back your Station Login and <B>Password</B> in order to check them for warnings, praises, etc. If you do not pass the screening nothing negative will happen to your account. Lastly, You can also enter multiple accounts you may own.<P>John Green,<BR>Lead Beta Tester<BR>Verant Inc.<BR></font><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>The reason this email scam looks so compelling, is that, per the player reporting this, the email address this came from was an @verant.com address.  We are currently looking into this further.  If you do receive this email, please email a copy of it in rich text format preferably, to   <A HREF="mailto:EQModerator@station.sony.com">EQModerator@station.sony.com</A>  By the way, we do not have a John Green, lead tester, at our company.  Also, remember that we <B>Never</B> ask for your password by email.  The only times it is asked for is for those applying at http:\\guideapp.everquest.com to become a guide, and when logging into EverQuest.  So, please do not fall for this scam.<BR>Thanks and safe journeys!<BR>Auric<BR>  <IMG SRC="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/cool.gif"><p>[Note: This message has been edited by ubbadmin]


