rd will be e-mailed to you, using the e-mail address you provided during registration. You will need the following information when you fill out the form:<P>Your Station Name<BR>Your ZIP/Postal Code<BR>Your Birth date (mm/dd/yy)<P>If you do not receive a new password, you will need to call Customer Support at 1-(858) 537-0898 or Email accounts@station.sony.com and provide the following information:<P>- Real Name<BR>- Station Name<BR>- Birth date<BR>- Address with Zip Code<BR>- Your original Account Key (found on the back of your CD case)<BR>- The last six digits of the Credit Card on file.<P>Once you have verified this info, we can update your email address and reset your password.<P><B>Example 8:</B><P>Hail and well met all!<BR>I am including another two scams that have been currently going around. We want to keep you aware of these scams as much as possible. Please regularly come back to this thread to see if any other scams have been added to the list. Also, to clarify again, we at Sony Online Entertainment/Verant Interactive will <B>NEVER</B> ask for your password by email or in game. The only email addresses official SOE/Verant communications are done by, are @soe.sony.com, @station.sony.com or @verant.com. Keep in mind some scammers make it appear their email comes from an address here though.<BR>Safe journeys <BR>Auric<P><B>Example 8 explained:</B><P>    <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2"><P>I have read the many warnings on Everquest scams and I have heard of an idea you guys might want to post or something. What these people do is make a character that seems like a Verant employee (i.e. "VerantWorker" and similar names) and then they tell people that if they want to see a list of the new items <BR>in the expansion then they can just type in the away from keyboard message command and then their password. After the unsuspecting person types this in, the scammer quickly does a "/t" so that they get the password as an away message. I have heard of people doing this frequently on Diablo 2 and I have heard of some people who say they want to try this out on Everquest as well. Just thought you might like to know. <BR>-happystrudel <BR>Pippens <BR>lvl 13 Barbarian Warrior <BR>Quellious Server<P></font><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR><B>Example 9:</B><P>Here's another password scam, I received today by e-mail.<P><BR>    <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2"><P>Date: Sun, 29 Jul 2001 22:26:08 -0700 (PDT) <BR>From: Mark Loogon | Block Address | Add to Address Book <BR>Subject: Important!!! Please read <BR>To: <P>Hello citizen of Norrath. This mail is never<BR>unsolicited. Please reply with an attachment enclosed<BR>"take me off the list" if you choose to not recieve<BR>any e-mail that is affiliated with Everquest.<P>*******************************************************<P>As you may know, the expansion, "Shadows of Luclin" is<BR>still under development, but we at the developer's<BR>corner are looking for 75 or so players to accept our<BR>invitation as testers and analyzers for the upcoming<BR>expansion. The test server is schedule to be online<BR>on August 15.<P>If you accept, please reply with your EQ chat screen<BR>name (your login username) and your <B>password</B>.<P>-Sony EQ developers<P></font><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Auric.<P><B>Example 10:</B><P>Hello again. <BR>/sigh. Another scam to report to you here. I don't think many will fall for this one as one look at the spelling alone should bring up warning signs.<BR>Auric.<P><BR>    <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2"><P>GM Dayswan<BR>poon<BR>(8/15/01 8:37:44 am)<BR>Reply Verant [EDITED] me im gonna [EDITED] them<BR>-----------------------------------------------------------------------<BR>I am a GM on Sullon Zek server. I am quitting EQ couse Verant has screwed me over by deleating my oth