.to extension. For all of you that dont happen to know what that means, .to stands for Tonga. Sony Online Entertainment EverQuest Operations is located in San Diego, California, USA, not Tonga  Also, there are so many run on sentences in these examples. My English teachers would kill me if it were me (were I?) that wrote these correspondences. Another inconsistency is that we do not have an employee by the name of Matthew Young. Lastly, we would never use an email that has anonymous somewhere in the email address.<BR>Auric.<P><B>Example 25:</B><P>Here is another scam that is a variation of one of the listed scams above.<P><BR>    <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2">  <BR>  This is an email I received today, I expect it is a scam that you should<BR>know about.<BR>Date: Tue, 20 Nov 2001 15:57:51 -0800<BR>From: "<B>Brain</B> DeMarco" <[EDITED]@anonymous.to><BR>Subject: Verant Live Server Testing!<P>Your name has been randomly drawn to be a "Live Server Tester". A Live <BR>Server Tester is someone who is given items in game and buffed up in <BR>levels in return for testing for EverQuest Tech. To make this more <BR>clear, you will be given items of your choice, and will be put at the <BR>level of your choice (and on the server of your choice), however, you <BR>may *not* tell anyone in game of your buffing, or actions will be taken.<BR>Once you are buffed you are encouraged to hunt with friends, go on <BR>raids, play like you normally would. Should you accept Live Server <BR>Tester status you will be given a website where you will be able to talk<BR>with other Testers, and find help, tips or just chat. Another benefit of<BR>accepting tester status is that you only have to pay $4.95 per month on <BR>your account. We only ask that you play at least one hour per week <BR>(that's only four hours per month) on your buffed tester, playing more <BR>than this is greatly encouraged and welcome, but to maintain Liv