 said that through the email bot, you can change certain aspects of your character, such as level, race and class. This is supposed to be only for employees, but anyone can do it with the right code. I have figured it out, and tested it and it works everytime. Heres how you do it. You send an email, in the format below, to this email:<P>verant[EDITED]@fiberia.com<P>The above email is the bot that verant uses on a remote server.<P>In the subject, you put CIRS<BR>(i think this means character information recovery system, but im not 100% sure). You must put exactly CIRS in the subject, or it will just be forwarded as a tech support question.<P>In the body, on the first line, put your station name. Dont worry about caps.<P>On the second line, put the server name, the first name only. For example, Rallos for Rallos Zek.<P><B>On the third line, put your station password. {Scam alert!!!}</B><P>Make one empty line.<P>Now comes the fun part.<P>On the line after the empty one, the fifth one, you can put codes for your characters. (It affects all your characters on the server you supplied).<P>Level Select<BR>2888 0948 999XX<P>Where XX is the level, such as 09 or 34. Dont make this totally unrealistic, or the bots will catch it and you will have to do this whole email thing again. I made my level 30 monk on rallos zek go from 30 to 42, just by sending the email. Thats not all you can do. Separate each code by one line.<P>Here are some more codes.<P>Increase Hp Regeneration. (Permanent Chloroplast)<BR>9802 8686 9203 420<P><BR>Increase Speed (Permanent S.O.W.)<BR>9802 8686 0946 562<P><BR>Increase Mana Regeneration (Permanent Clarity)<BR>9802 8686 9203 846<P>Dont worry, if anything goes wrong, the email bot will just delete the email, and you will have to do it again. There is absolutely no risk involved, since you are sending your information to verant.<BR></font><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR><B>Example 30:</B><BR>   <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2"><BR>Not sure if this is a scam or not.<P>However, I did NOT open the attatchment. <BR>If you are new to EverQuest, or have just purchased one of the expansions (EverQuest: The Ruins of Kunark or EverQuest: Scars of Velious), this supplement contains information that you may find vital on your adventures. <BR>The PDF version of the manual at HYPERLINK  <A HREF="http://www.everquest.com" TARGET=_blank>http://www.everquest.com</A>  and this supplement make the files in your EverQuest directory labeled everquest_manual.doc and everquest_manual.txt obsolete. <BR><B>Attachment : manual.exe</B><BR></font><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Thanks to <B>Goishen</B> who posted this scam warning on The Newbie Zone.  <B>DO NOT</B> fall for this one.  The manual.exe file is probably either a keystroke recorder or back door virus.  Sony Online Entertainment does not send out .exe files to update the EverQuest data.  That is done through our patcher.  Regardless of where it appears this email came from, it is a scam to get you to execute their file that would then give the sender control of your computer or access to your station name and password information.  As <B>Reskrid</B> posted in the thread on the Newbie Zone about this scam:<BR>   <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2"><BR>Rule of Thumb. <BR>If email arrives and its not from a friend/coworker and you did not specifically request same, delete it. <BR>Even with the best Firewalls and Virus Scanners you won't be protected from new threats. Smart use is your best defense.<BR></font><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Brian De Marco<BR>Auric<P><BR><B>Example 31:</B><BR>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2"><BR>-----Original Message-----<BR> From: EDITED@rn.com [mailto:EDITED@rn.com]<BR> Sent: Saturday, April 20, 2002 7:53 AM<BR> To: {EDITED}<BR> Subject: EverQuest Beta Testing<P><BR> Hail, Everquest customer! Your email address was randomly selected <BR> from our database of players. We have been asking these select few players <BR> whether or not they would like to participate in the upcoming Planes <BR> of Power beta test, to celebrate the 3rd anniversary of EverQuest!<P> If you agree to sign up for the PoP beta test you will get to try <BR> out exclusive Planes of Power armor, weapons and spells. Also, you <BR> will have access to the new PoP zones. If this wasn't enough, to <BR> urge our player base into helping us out, we will give the first 100 players to sign up a<BR> superb piece of equipment based on your character class and race. You will <BR> be notified via email with testing details once the server comes up. <BR> In order to be accepted into the Planes of Power Beta Test, You will<BR> need to email us back your Station Login and <B>password</B> in order to <BR> check them for warnings, praises, etc. If you do not pass the <BR> screening nothing negative will happen to your account. Good Luck and Safe Travels!!!<P> <B>Damien Green</B>,<BR> Lead Beta Tester<BR> <B>Verant Inc.</B><BR></font><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>We do not have a Damien Green who works at Sony Online Entertainment.  Also, we <B>NEVER</B> ask for players passwords through email.  We never use email addresses other than @station.sony.com or @soe.sony.com.  This scam uses a @rn.com and a @fiberia.com email address.  This hopefully right off the bat causes people to be suspicious.<P>Brian De Marco<BR>Auric<P><BR><B>Example 33:</B><BR> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2"><BR>The <B>Verant team</B> has been given a chance to search the database of The Player<BR>Auction past transactions. Starting this week we will now be completely<BR>taking all action in stopping the process of account selling/trading . We<BR>have located over 25 account trading and account selling auctions with in<BR>the past week. Generally we know the owners of these accounts were notified<BR>that account trading/selling /stealing is totally illegal with in our<BR>covenant rules.<BR>To give you a basic overview what we do in this situation is permanently<BR>delete the account and the IP host of its current user from our login access<BR>screen. Once this is done we have organized vote from all the<BR>representatives and rank members of verant in which we should even precede<BR>more in depth in this matter.<BR>If chosen, depending on the matter we could choose to simply have your<BR>account banned or depending on the vote have you put forward for Misusage of<BR>our account.<P>Here at the <B>Station, Sony Verant</B> we hate banning citizens of our community<BR>or doing anything to there accounts unless it's a positive change.<BR>Importantly we want our game Everquest to be fun and exciting as an everyday<BR>experience.<P>If you have any questions please refer to the GM that Verant has chosen for<BR>you.<P>Hello Norman Freeman  here,<BR>I am supposed to ask you if you have any questions about what is going to<BR>happen to your account. I personally viewed your Player Auction and to be<BR>honest with you I myself do not believe your account should be terminated. I<BR>do however believe you should get a warning or just a temporary suspension.<BR>As a <B>Verant Coe represenitive</B> I have the ability to change the status of<BR>what might happen to your account with in the next four to five days. What I<BR>am going to do is ask you some account information. Basically I just want to<BR>make sure this account is actually yours.<P>If the account is yours then I will see it has a warning applied.<P>Norman Freeman<BR><B>Verant Sony Interactive</B><P>Please Answer the following information in your reply to this E-Mail:<BR>And return to the follow address.<BR>EDITED@mail.com<P><> The name you gave us when you first filled out the Everquest Registration<BR>Form<BR><> Your Everquest Station Name<BR><> The full name on the credit card supporting your account.<BR><B>Your current Station Password</B><BR>CD key is not required.<P>It may take a week to resolve this info, if you cannot complete any of the<BR>information, please reply to the below email address<BR>and explain why and to the attention of Norman Freeman.<P>mailto:EDITED@mail.com<BR></font><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>  We do have an employee named Norman Freeman.  However, this is obviously a scam as they ask for the password of the account.  As a reminder, we will Never ask for your password by email.  Do not fall for this scam....  If you send them your station name and password, you will be compromising the security of your account.  The email here is not from our company.  We only use @station.sony.com and @soe.sony.com addresses.  This scam uses an @mail.com email address and tries to make it appear it is coming from within Sony Online Entertainment.<P>Brian De Marco<BR>Auric<BR><p>[Note: This message has been edited by ubbadmin]




